The comment claims `System.Type.GetType` “scans all loaded assemblies on each call”. For non-assembly-qualified names (like "System.DateOnly"), `Type.GetType(string)` only probes corelib and the calling/executing assembly (it doesn’t iterate every loaded assembly), so this rationale is misleading. Consider rewording to describe the real cost (repeated reflection-based name resolution) without asserting an assembly scan.
```suggestion
    // date/time property. Repeating reflection-based type-name resolution for
    // every field in a large schema adds measurable design-time overhead.
```

`headersStr` parsing drops headers whose values contain '=' (e.g., `Authorization=Basic dXNlcjpwYXNz==`), because `x.Split '='` yields length > 2 and the header is ignored. Split on the first '=' only (e.g., `Split('=', 2)`) and keep the remainder as the value (optionally also trim whitespace).
```suggestion
                    let pair = x.Split([|'='|], 2)
                    if (pair.Length = 2) then Some(pair[0].Trim(), pair[1].Trim()) else None)
```

This DateTimeOffset form-url-encoding test only checks that the output contains the date, which isn’t sufficient to prove ISO 8601 / round-trip formatting (a locale-specific string could still contain `2024-06-15`). Consider asserting the decoded `ts` value equals `dto.ToString("O")` (including time and offset) by parsing/decoding the query string.
```suggestion

            let encodedValue = body.Substring("ts=".Length)
            let decodedValue = WebUtility.UrlDecode(encodedValue)

            decodedValue |> shouldEqual (dto.ToString("O"))
```

The inline comment mentions the dot being "within the valid prefix", but the dot is in the definition path portion (after the prefix). Consider rewording to avoid implying the prefix contains the dot (e.g., refer to the scanned type-name segment instead).
```suggestion
    // The dot before "my-type" is in the scanned definition-name segment after
    // the prefix; the hyphen stops the scan, so LastIndexOf('.') finds that dot.
```

This introduces a second ad-hoc unique-name generator (`Seq.initInfinite` + `Set.contains`) even though the codebase already has `UniqueNameGenerator` with the same suffixing convention (and case-insensitive uniqueness). Consider factoring this into a shared helper (or reusing `UniqueNameGenerator` by seeding it with `usedNames`) to avoid future divergence in how “unique names” are defined.
```suggestion
                    // conflict with any OpenAPI parameter already in use, using the shared
                    // UniqueNameGenerator to keep suffixing and case sensitivity consistent.
                    let nameGen = UniqueNameGenerator()
                    usedNames |> Set.iter (fun n -> nameGen.Claim n |> ignore)
                    let ctParamName = nameGen.Claim "cancellationToken"
```

`ConcurrentDictionary.GetOrAdd` may invoke the valueFactory multiple times under contention, and only one result is actually stored. Because the factory sets `added <- true` unconditionally, callers that *lose* the race can still see `added = true` and start `invalidationFunction`, reintroducing redundant timers (and possibly expensive `valueFactory` work) when multiple threads hit a missing key concurrently. Consider restructuring to detect a successful insert (e.g., `TryGetValue` + compute + `TryAdd`/retry) and only start the timer when the add succeeds.
```suggestion
            // First, try to retrieve an existing value without creating a new one.
            match dict.TryGetValue(key) with
            | true, (existingValue, _) ->
                // Key already present: return the existing value and do not start a new timer.
                existingValue
            | _ ->
                // Key not present: compute the value and attempt to add it.
                let value = valueFactory()
                let entry = (value, DateTime.UtcNow)

                if dict.TryAdd(key, entry) then
                    // This call successfully inserted the value: start invalidation.
                    invalidationFunction key |> Async.Start
                    value
                else
                    // Another thread inserted the value concurrently: return the stored value.
                    let storedValue, _ = dict.[key]
                    storedValue }
```

This test assumes passing `null` into `toQueryParams` is equivalent to `Option<string>.None` and should yield `[]`. In `RuntimeHelpers.toQueryParams`, `null` hits the fallback branch and produces `[ (name, null) ]` (which is only skipped later when `createHttpRequest` filters null values). Update the assertion to match `toQueryParams`’s direct output, or move this check to a `createHttpRequest`-level test instead.
```suggestion
    let ``toQueryParams handles null input via fallback branch``() =
        // Passing null directly does not go through Option-handling logic; it hits the
        // fallback branch and produces a single (name, null) pair. Any filtering of
        // null values happens later (e.g., in createHttpRequest), not in toQueryParams.
        let result = toQueryParams "q" null stubClient
        result |> shouldEqual [ ("q", null) ]
```

The comment states "Swashbuckle doesn't generate 'additionalProperties' in Swagger 2.0 for dictionaries". However, if the tests have been removed due to a known limitation in the test server setup rather than an actual issue in SwaggerProvider itself, this should be made clearer. Consider adding information about whether this is a temporary workaround and if there's a plan to re-enable these tests once Swashbuckle is fixed, or if this represents a permanent limitation.
```suggestion
// NOTE: Dictionary tests for the Swagger 2.0 endpoint are disabled here because the Swashbuckle test server
// (and its Swagger 2.0 generator) does not emit 'additionalProperties' for dictionary types.
// The generated swagger.json currently contains: {"type": "object"} instead of
// {"type": "object", "additionalProperties": {"$ref": "#/definitions/PointClass"}}.
// This is a limitation of the Swashbuckle/Swagger 2.0 test setup, not of SwaggerProvider itself.
// The corresponding OpenAPI 3.0 tests in v3/Swashbuckle.ReturnControllers.Tests.fs validate dictionary support.
// See: tests/SwaggerProvider.ProviderTests/v3/Swashbuckle.ReturnControllers.Tests.fs for working dictionary tests.
// If Swashbuckle's Swagger 2.0 generator is ever updated to emit 'additionalProperties' correctly,
// these v2 dictionary-return tests can be re-enabled.
```

The link-local address check using `StartsWith \"169.254.\"` is vulnerable to the same bypass as the other IP checks. A hostname like `169.254.1.1.example.com` would incorrectly match. Use proper IP address parsing to ensure the entire host is actually an IP address before performing range checks.
```suggestion
            // Try to parse host as IP address
            let isIp, ipAddr = System.Net.IPAddress.TryParse(host)

            // Block localhost and loopback
            if
                host = "localhost"
                || (isIp && (ipAddr.Equals(System.Net.IPAddress.Loopback) || ipAddr.Equals(System.Net.IPAddress.IPv6Loopback)))
                || host = "0.0.0.0"
            then
                failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from localhost/loopback addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host

            // Block private IP ranges (RFC 1918) and link-local only if host is an IP address
            if isIp then
                let bytes = ipAddr.GetAddressBytes()
                // IPv4 private ranges
                let isPrivate =
                    (bytes.[0] = 10uy) ||
                    (bytes.[0] = 192uy && bytes.[1] = 168uy) ||
                    (bytes.[0] = 172uy && bytes.[1] >= 16uy && bytes.[1] <= 31uy)
                if isPrivate then
                    failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from private IP addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host
                // Link-local 169.254.0.0/16
                let isLinkLocal = (bytes.[0] = 169uy && bytes.[1] = 254uy)
                if isLinkLocal then
                    failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from link-local addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host
```

The private IP range validation using `StartsWith` is vulnerable to bypass. For example, `10.0.0.1.example.com` would incorrectly match `host.StartsWith \"10.\"`. Use proper IP address parsing with `System.Net.IPAddress.TryParse` to verify the host is actually an IP address, then check if it falls within the private ranges using proper IP address comparison.
```suggestion
            // Block localhost and loopback, and private IP ranges using proper IP address parsing
            let isIp, ipAddr = System.Net.IPAddress.TryParse(host)
            if isIp then
                // Loopback
                if System.Net.IPAddress.IsLoopback(ipAddr) || ipAddr.ToString() = "0.0.0.0" then
                    failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from localhost/loopback addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host
                // Private IPv4 ranges
                let bytes = ipAddr.GetAddressBytes()
                let isPrivate =
                    // 10.0.0.0/8
                    (ipAddr.AddressFamily = System.Net.Sockets.AddressFamily.InterNetwork && bytes.[0] = 10uy)
                    // 172.16.0.0/12
                    || (ipAddr.AddressFamily = System.Net.Sockets.AddressFamily.InterNetwork && bytes.[0] = 172uy && bytes.[1] >= 16uy && bytes.[1] <= 31uy)
                    // 192.168.0.0/16
                    || (ipAddr.AddressFamily = System.Net.Sockets.AddressFamily.InterNetwork && bytes.[0] = 192uy && bytes.[1] = 168uy)
                    // Link-local 169.254.0.0/16
                    || (ipAddr.AddressFamily = System.Net.Sockets.AddressFamily.InterNetwork && bytes.[0] = 169uy && bytes.[1] = 254uy)
                if isPrivate then
                    failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from private or link-local IP addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host
            else
                // Block localhost by name
                if host = "localhost" then
                    failwithf "Cannot fetch schemas from localhost/loopback addresses: %s (set SsrfProtection=false for development)" host
```

